                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d741">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">890D.01/637: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Consul at Beirut</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gwynn</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-09-03T21:00:00-04:00"
                            >September 3, 1942—9 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>146. The Department very much appreciates the full and complete reports you have
                    sent, with particular reference to your 325, September 3 [<hi rend="italic"
                        >1</hi>], 10 p.m.</p>
                <p>The situation in Beirut however is but one phase of our necessary considerations
                    of the British-Fighting French situation. Therefore while it is our hope you
                    will continue to keep the Department fully informed, it is at the same time most
                    desirable that you should not offer to undertake or accept any responsibilities
                    in this situation without <pb facs="0643" n="631" xml:id="pg_631"/> previous
                    reference to the Department. In this particular connection paragraph 2 of your
                    telegram under reference is cited.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
